	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_25959929"><p>You're right. Also Stroustrup had clearly pointed (in other argument lines) that C is not the better way to learn C++ (or OO in general):</p><p>BEGIN EXCERPT from <a href="http://www.research.att.com/~bs/new_learning.pdf" title="att.com">http://www.research.att.com/~bs/new_learning.pdf</a> [att.com] :</p><p>
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; One conventional answer to the question ''Which subset of C++ should I learn first?'' is ''The C subset<br>of C++.'' In my considered opinion, that's not a good answer. The C-first approach leads to an early focus<br>on low-level details. It also obscures programming style and design issues by forces the student to face<br>many technical difficulties to express anything interesting.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_25959929">
