	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_25961763"><p><div class="quote"><p>You're right. Also Stroustrup had clearly pointed (in other argument lines) that C is not the better way to learn C++ (or OO in general):</p></div><p>Somebody quoting Stroustrup on the topic of computer languages... seriously?  C++ is like legalese -- it's impenetrable to read, full of unintended consequences, and even though it's spelled out in excruciating detail what it says is still open to interpretation.</p><p>Not only is C the <i>first</i> subset of C++ that programmers should learn, it is the <i>only</i> subset of C++ they should learn.</p><p>And I argue that C actually teaches people more about object-oriented that most other languages, because it teaches them in no uncertain terms <i>why</i> you should use objects.  It's harder to realize why you don't just make fields public until you've seen global variables in a C program.</p><p>Then Java teaches you how to do OO where you are not allowed to 'cheat' by replacing methods at runtime, or calling methods that don't exist, etc.  And JavaScript takes all that and gives you LISP power.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_25961763">
